Even this seems to be an issue

```python
idx = a > 0.5
c = b[idx]
```

is `boolean indexing` supported?

Hi @dashey,

Attaching the ONNX model will help, but this seems like an invalid ONNX model to me. As the error message says, it seems to have bound bool type to indices input which deviates from spec - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Gather. Hence, this is an invalid model/graph (present in the error status). The model seems to be missing node names and hence the name section in the error message is empty - `in node () is invalid`.

If you upload the model, I ll help you find the specific problematic node and then you can use the info to open a bug against the base framework/converter you are using to obtain the model. As such this doesn't seem to be an ORT issue.

Thanks!
Also, ideally the ONNX model checker should do such type validations. There is an issue tracking this - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2292.

I will send you the model. I tried `masked_select` but that is not supported either for the exporter

>  KeyError: u'masked_select

Can you try making indices int32 or int64 type ? Only that is supported per ONNX spec. 

I am happy to take a look at the model to make sure it really is a model issue, but unfortunately exporting it to an ONNX complaint format is not something I can help with. You need to get this help from the base project/ converter...
I can use `torch.where` to convert to absolute indices. But lack of support for masked selection (and boolean indices) seems like a big deficiency
Spoke offline with @dashesy and pointed out the exact issue in the model he shared offline. Since this is not an ORT issue (the ONNX model was invalid per spec), closing this issue.

Added issues [here](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/26034) and [here](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2302). Also added [this issue](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/26035) to attach a random name in the exporter for better debugging

issue.body:
##  Bug

Boolean indexing is not supported in ONNX and the [exported models are invalid](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1807), as suggested by ONNX instead of Gather [use where to export to onnx](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2302)

## To Reproduce

Steps to reproduce the behavior:

```python
idx = b > 0.5
c = d[idx]
```

## Environment

PyTorch version: 1.2.0
Is debug build: No
CUDA used to build PyTorch: 10.0.130

OS: Ubuntu 16.04.6 LTS
GCC version: (Ubuntu 5.4.0-6ubuntu1~16.04.11) 5.4.0 20160609
CMake version: version 3.14.0

Python version: 2.7
Is CUDA available: Yes
CUDA runtime version: Could not collect
GPU models and configuration: GPU 0: GeForce GTX 1070
Nvidia driver version: 418.40.04
cuDNN version: /usr/local/lib/libcudnn.so.5.1.10

Versions of relevant libraries:
[pip] mictorch==0.0.1
[pip] numpy==1.16.4
[pip] torch==1.2.0
[pip] torchvision==0.4.0
[conda] Could not collect

## Additional context

Workaround is to avoid boolean indexing and use `where` and `nonzero`, but if boolean indexing is already used using `Gather` is incorrect. Another solution is for `Gather` to accept boolean indexing.

when I use 'torch.where', the following errors are shown.

my code is
```
        x=self.linear(inputs)

        x = F.relu(x)

        x_max = torch.max(x, dim=1, keepdim=True)[0]

        x_repeat = x_max.repeat(1, inputs.shape[1], 1)
        x_concatenated = torch.cat([x, x_repeat], dim=2)
        idx=torch.where(x_concatenated>5)[0]
        #idx=torch.nonzero(x_concatenated>5,as_tuple=True)[0]
        x_concatenated=x_concatenated[idx]
        return x_concatenated
```
@wangguojun2018 `torch.where` semantics is different from `np.where`, you have to specify 2 more tensors for True and False elements. Please refer to the `torch.where` docs

> **Note:** Creating this issue using @charleygros's comment on https://github.com/neuropoly/spinalcordtoolbox/pull/3321#issuecomment-810725960

We've tried converting the `.pt` version of this model to `.ONNX`, and it appears to work. However, an error occurs when loading the .ONNX model file using `onnxruntime.InferenceSession(model_path)`: 

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/spinalcordtoolbox/scripts/sct_deepseg.py", line 245, in <module>
    main(sys.argv[1:])
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/spinalcordtoolbox/scripts/sct_deepseg.py", line 207, in main
    nii_lst, target_lst = imed_inference.segment_volume(path_model, input_filenames, options=options)
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/python/envs/venv_sct/lib/python3.6/site-packages/ivadomed/inference.py", line 264, in segment_volume
    preds = model(img) if fname_model.endswith('.pt') else onnx_inference(fname_model, img)
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/python/envs/venv_sct/lib/python3.6/site-packages/ivadomed/inference.py", line 377, in onnx_inference
    ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(model_path)
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/python/envs/venv_sct/lib/python3.6/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/session.py", line 158, in __init__
    self._load_model(providers or [])
  File "/home/GRAMES.POLYMTL.CA/chgroc/spinalcordtoolbox/python/envs/venv_sct/lib/python3.6/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/session.py", line 177, in _load_model
    self._sess.load_model(providers)
onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.InvalidGraph: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 10 : INVALID_GRAPH : This is an invalid model. Type Error: Type 'tensor(bool)' of input parameter (281) of operator (ScatterND) in node (ScatterND_160) is invalid.
```

This looks to be the same error message as https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1807, https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2848, etc. (I haven't looked at the model definition, though, so I can't confirm if the problem/solution from those issues are appropriate here.)
